qas.question: What other term is given to the director of studies?
With whom does the primary responsibility for a student's leaning lie?
Who designed the learning buildings at Eton?
Are living houses and classrooms seperate or conjoined?
Who was one of the first House Master's?
In what year were tutor's introduced to Eton?
How often have new buildings for housing appeared at Eton?
What is New Schools colloquially known as?

context: The primary responsibility for a boy's studies lies with his <a1_0>House Master<a1_0/>, but he is assisted by an additional director of studies, known as a <a0_0>tutor<a0_0/>. Classes, colloquially known as "<b7_0>divs<b7_0/>" (divisions), are organised on a School basis; the classrooms are <a3_0>separate<a3_0/> from the houses. New school buildings have appeared for teaching purposes <b6_0>every decade or so<b6_0/> since New Schools, designed by <a2_0><b4_0>Henry Woodyer<b4_0/><a2_0/> and built <b5_0>1861<b5_0/>-3. Despite the introduction of modern technology, the external appearance and locations of many of the classrooms have remained unchanged for a long time.
